Step 3 server.js (clean version)

Here is a fixed version of your server with routing + JSON API support:

js
import fs from "fs";
import http from "http";
import url from "url";
import path from "path";
import { fileURLToPath } from "url";

const __filename = fileURLToPath(import.meta.url);
const __dirname = path.dirname(__filename);

const port = 8080;

const mimeTypes = {
  html: "text/html",
  js: "application/javascript",
  css: "text/css",
  jpg: "image/jpg",
  png: "image/png",
  jpeg: "image/jpeg",
  svg: "image/svg+xml",
  ico: "image/x-icon",
  json: "application/json"
};

// Your API routes
const routes = {
  "/api/test": (req, res, data) => {
    res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": "application/json" });
    res.end(JSON.stringify({ message: "Backend connected!", data }));
  }
};

http
  .createServer((req, res) => {
    let parsedURL = url.parse(req.url, true);
    let pathname = parsedURL.pathname;

    // Handle API routes
    if (routes[pathname]) {
      if (req.method === "POST") {
        let body = "";
        req.on("data", chunk => (body += chunk));
        req.on("end", () => {
          let data = {};
          try {
            data = JSON.parse(body);
          } catch {}
          routes[pathname](req, res, data);
        });
        return;
      }

      // GET
      routes[pathname](req, res, parsedURL.query);
      return;
    }

    // Serve static files
    let filePath = path.join(
      __dirname,
      "public",
      pathname === "/" ? "index.html" : pathname
    );

    if (!fs.existsSync(filePath)) {
      filePath = path.join(__dirname, "public", "index.html");
    }

    const ext = path.extname(filePath).slice(1);
    const mime = mimeTypes[ext] || "text/plain";

    fs.readFile(filePath, (err, content) => {
      if (err) {
        res.writeHead(500);
        res.end("Server Error");
        return;
      }
      res.writeHead(200, { "Content-Type": mime });
      res.end(content);
    });
  })
  .listen(port, () => console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${port}`));

This supports:

POST API
JSON parsing

explain how to use count effect
ChatGPT said:

Ah! You mean how to use useEffect in React for something like a counter effect? Lets go step by step.

Ill explain clearly and practically.

1 Basic Counter with useState

Before useEffect, you need a state to store your counter:

jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increase</button>
    </div>
  );
}

  • count current value

  • setCount function to update the value

Clicking the button increases the counter.

2 Add useEffect to Watch the Counter

useEffect runs side effects when something changes, e.g., log every time the counter updates:

jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // This effect runs every time `count` changes
  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Counter changed:", count);
  }, [count]); // <- dependency array

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increase</button>
    </div>
  );
}

Explanation:

  • useEffect(() => { ... }, [count])
    Runs the effect only when count changes.

  • If you put [] (empty array), it runs once on mount.

  • If you omit the second argument, it runs on every render.

3 Example: Automatic Counter with Interval

You can use useEffect to increment the counter automatically every second:

jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from "react";

function AutoCounter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    const interval = setInterval(() => {
      setCount(prev => prev + 1);
    }, 1000);

    // Cleanup to prevent memory leaks
    return () => clearInterval(interval);
  }, []); // empty array  run only once on mount

  return <p>Count: {count}</p>;
}

Notes:

  • setCount(prev => prev + 1) ensures you always use the latest value

  • return () => clearInterval(interval) cleans up when component unmounts

4 Key Points about useEffect

  1. Dependencies ([count] or []) decide when it runs

  2. Side effects can be anything:

    • Logging

    • Fetching data

    • Updating local storage

    • Subscribing to events

  3. Always cleanup if your effect creates intervals, subscriptions, or timers.

5 Quick Example: Count Effect + API Call

jsx
useEffect(() => {
  fetch(`/api/count/${count}`)
    .then(res => res.json())
    .then(data => console.log(data));
}, [count]);

  • This runs every time the counter changes

  • Perfect for syncing state with a backend

The brackets in useEffect, called the dependency array, tell React which values to watch.

  • If any value in the array changes, React runs the effect again.

  • If the array is empty [], the effect runs only once when the component mounts.

jsx

  console.log("Component mounted");

  console.log("Render happened");
}); // no array  runs every render

So yes the bracket contains the variables React watches to decide when to rerun the effect.

Yes! You dont need to include the full URL if your React app is running on the same domain/port as your Node.js server.

Example:

Your server has this route:

js

  • Browser automatically makes the request to http://localhost:8080/api/test

2 Fetch with absolute URL:

js
fetch("http://localhost:8080/api/test")
  .then(res => res.json())
  .then(data => console.log(data));

  • Works the same way

  • Only needed if your frontend and backend are on different domains or ports

Best Practice

  • If frontend & backend run together always use relative URLs (/api/...)

  • If frontend runs on a different port (e.g., React dev server :5173 and Node :8080) you need absolute URLs or a proxy setup

js

  .then(res => res.json())

        value={price}

export default AddProduct;

can i use this const handleChange = (e)=>{ const value = e.target.value return value } and since its returning a value i just put it inside the setState
ChatGPT said:

Almost! But not quite in React, you cannot directly return a value from an event handler and expect it to update state automatically.

Heres why:

  • handleChange gets called on every keystroke.

  • Returning a value from it does nothing by itself React ignores the return value.

  • You must call setState inside the handler to update your state.

Correct way:

jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function InputExample() {
  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  const handleChange = (e) => {
    const value = e.target.value;
    setName(value); // <-- update state here
  };

  return (
    <input
      type="text"
      value={name}
      onChange={handleChange} // pass the handler
    />
  );
}

  • setName(value) updates the React state

  • return value would do nothing

Alternative inline version:

jsx
<input
  type="text"
  value={name}
  onChange={(e) => setName(e.target.value)}
/>

  • No separate handleChange needed

  • Works exactly the same

So, the key point:

You cannot just return the value from the handler. Always call setState(value) inside the handler to update React state.

You said:
what if im gonna use it for two inputs
ChatGPT said:

Ah, perfect! If you have two (or more) inputs, the common React pattern is to use one state object and a single handleChange function that updates the correct field based on the inputs name.

Heres how you do it:

Example: Two Inputs (Product Name + Price)

jsx
import { useState } from "react";

function AddProduct() {
  const [formData, setFormData] = useState({
    name: "",
    price: ""
  });

  const handleChange = (e) => {
    const { name, value } = e.target;
    // Update only the changed field
    setFormData(prev => ({
      ...prev,       // keep other fields
      [name]: value  // update the field that changed
    }));
  };

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    console.log(formData); // { name: "...", price: "..." }

    // Send data to backend
    fetch("/api/add-product", {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
      body: JSON.stringify(formData)
    })
      .then(res => res.json())
      .then(data => console.log("Response:", data));
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input
        type="text"
        name="name"           // important!
        placeholder="Product Name"
        value={formData.name}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />
      <input
        type="number"
        name="price"          // important!
        placeholder="Price"
        value={formData.price}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />
      <button type="submit">Add Product</button>
    </form>
  );
}

export default AddProduct;

How it works:

  1. State object: formData = { name: "", price: "" }

  2. Input name attribute: used to identify which field changed

  3. Single handleChange function: updates only the field that changed

  4. ...prev spread operator: keeps other fields intact

Why this is better than separate useState per input

  • Easier to scale to 510 inputs

  • Easier to submit all data at once

  • Cleaner code with one handler
